But last night one Tory backbencher said David Cameron would be able to reduce gas and electricity bills further if he stopped listening to his Liberal Democrat colleagues and axed the green levies altogether.

George Osborne’s Autumn Statement on Thursday will include a range of changes, including a freeze in business taxes for small firms, and a £250million boost to the British Business Bank to help small companies access funding.

And he confirmed yesterday that it would include an announcement that the government would pay for some green measures currently included in people’s bills - cutting the cost for families across the country.

In addition, energy firms will be given two years longer to hit targets on the insulation of homes, enabling costs to consumers to be spread out.

The moves were welcomed by the energy firms - and the Chancellor said he was certain that the average £50 saving from slashing the Energy Company Obligation - would be passed on by energy firms to consumers.

